It is thought nearly 5 million clandestine abortions are carried out every year - more than any other country in the world.

The Brazilian government was taken to court when they introduced a bill to give pregnant women free exclusively free access to the morning-after pill (levonorgestrel), the first oral emergency contraceptive pill in the world that stops pregnancy by 72 hours.

However, the Supreme Court ruled that it could not be introduced back in June 2014.

After the ruling, the country claimed they would no longer stipulate access to the pill, whenever it was needed.

Many hoped that this would allow women to take charge of their own reproductive health. However the proposal was annulled by then-Health minister Arthur Chioro.

This news comes after Dutch government announced they would no longer pay for morning-after pills either.

What can be done?

The illegalising of abortion was established to protect the embryo's right to life during pregnancy, therefore both Gesthuizen and Samson of the Socialist Party have called for an amendment to Article 6, this would allow for abortion within wider circumstances.

As it stands, the current law allows for abortion if the pregnancy is a result of rape, or pregnancy endanger the physical or psychological health of the pregnant woman.

Gesthuizen argued that this is an "old law", which needs to be modernised. "
